WEBVTT

1
00:01:18.817 --> 00:01:20.152
- Hey, Jim.
- Good morning.


2
00:01:25.115 --> 00:01:26.116
- Thanks.
- Thank you.


3
00:01:28.202 --> 00:01:29.722
That all you're traveling with, honey?

4
00:01:31.955 --> 00:01:32.956
I'm Sharon.

5
00:01:51.683 --> 00:01:52.726
You wear a medium?

6
00:01:55.812 --> 00:01:56.813
Okay…

7
00:01:58.607 --> 00:02:02.986
Cell phone is prepaid. Somewhere on here,
it tells you the number.


8
00:02:04.488 --> 00:02:06.490
I was trying to think
what else to get you.


9
00:02:06.573 --> 00:02:08.574
It's always different with each person.

10
00:02:09.116 --> 00:02:11.912
Eye drops, hair spray, whatever…

11
00:02:12.412 --> 00:02:15.290
Last guy, he liked to use
conditioner instead of shaving cream.


12
00:02:15.791 --> 00:02:17.459
You just let me know what you need.

13
00:02:25.425 --> 00:02:26.969
Do you need me to go slower?

14
00:02:53.203 --> 00:02:54.371
Let me help you.

15
00:02:59.543 --> 00:03:01.837
There you go. Good.

16
00:03:07.801 --> 00:03:10.262
Well, I'm sure
you're more of an adventurer.


17
00:03:11.221 --> 00:03:14.725
I can't stand planes.
Don't like being up in the air


18
00:03:14.808 --> 00:03:17.394
and all the people
breathing down your neck.


19
00:03:19.605 --> 00:03:20.606
Good job, honey.

20
00:03:25.193 --> 00:03:26.194
All right.

21
00:03:26.695 --> 00:03:31.950
Now, let's stand up slowly.

22
00:03:35.120 --> 00:03:38.665
Bathrooms can be dangerous.

23
00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:43.378
Here, let me help you.

24
00:04:11.365 --> 00:04:14.701
Frank liked naproxen better than Advil.

25
00:04:15.744 --> 00:04:17.746
He had bursitis in his shoulder.

26
00:04:18.580 --> 00:04:21.083
He worked in the plant,
packing TV dinners.


27
00:04:22.167 --> 00:04:26.588
I wouldn't eat 'em. All that ammonium,
probably what got him sick.


28
00:04:28.590 --> 00:04:29.800
How long ago was that?

29
00:04:30.384 --> 00:04:31.385
Nine years.

30
00:04:32.761 --> 00:04:36.473
I got so good at taking care of him, I
thought, why can't I do that for a living?


31
00:04:36.557 --> 00:04:38.850
So I went back
to school and got licensed.

32
00:04:39.351 --> 00:04:40.811
What a miserable life.

33
00:04:49.152 --> 00:04:50.153
I'm so sorry.

34
00:04:51.697 --> 00:04:54.616
It's okay.
People say things they don't mean.


35
00:04:55.993 --> 00:04:59.246
Sometimes they can't remember words.
It'll get easier.


36
00:05:10.966 --> 00:05:12.759
Do you remember this man's name?

37
00:05:16.263 --> 00:05:18.849
John Jones.

38
00:05:25.647 --> 00:05:26.815
Mary Black?

39
00:05:35.282 --> 00:05:36.283
I have no idea.

40
00:05:38.660 --> 00:05:40.954
Okay. And now with the other hand?

41
00:05:48.503 --> 00:05:50.005
You got it.

42
00:05:52.299 --> 00:05:54.635
Good job. It's all right. Going back.

43
00:06:38.428 --> 00:06:39.555
Sharon!

44
00:06:42.432 --> 00:06:43.433
Sharon!

45
00:06:47.479 --> 00:06:49.481
You're okay, honey.

46
00:06:50.732 --> 00:06:55.028
It's okay. Just breathe.

47
00:06:55.696 --> 00:06:56.780
Listen to me.

48
00:06:59.741 --> 00:07:02.578
It's okay. You're okay.

49
00:07:03.203 --> 00:07:06.707
That's it. Just breathe.

50
00:07:07.499 --> 00:07:10.627
In… and out.

51
00:07:12.337 --> 00:07:15.382
In and out.

52
00:07:21.847 --> 00:07:24.892
One more.

53
00:07:27.436 --> 00:07:28.478
You're doing great.

54
00:07:30.230 --> 00:07:34.526
Good. This is a big one.
They won't be like this later.


55
00:07:44.870 --> 00:07:45.871
Are you with me?

56
00:08:21.240 --> 00:08:22.241
Thank you.

57
00:08:37.881 --> 00:08:40.217
You wanna go for a drive
before it gets dark?


58
00:08:50.644 --> 00:08:52.521
Let's take this right into town.

59
00:09:04.324 --> 00:09:05.324
Look at you.

60
00:09:09.371 --> 00:09:10.372
You're ready to go.

61
00:09:27.014 --> 00:09:32.019
Pull over. You need to pull over
just to the side of the road. Right here.


62
00:09:42.654 --> 00:09:43.780
I'm sorry.

63
00:09:44.281 --> 00:09:45.365
It's okay.

64
00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:48.911
I know this is hard.

65
00:09:49.912 --> 00:09:54.625
This isn't hard.
Driving a car shouldn't be a victory.


66
00:09:57.377 --> 00:10:00.797
I mean leaving. 
Transition can be hard.

67
00:10:02.007 --> 00:10:05.886
If you're not feeling ready,
we can look into extending your stay.


68
00:10:07.304 --> 00:10:08.513
I can't pay for that.

69
00:10:10.224 --> 00:10:11.934
I should be getting back anyway.

70
00:10:12.517 --> 00:10:13.727
Back home.

71
00:10:14.770 --> 00:10:17.397
No, back to work. Redeploy.

72
00:10:22.152 --> 00:10:26.532
You've made a lot of progress, but you're
not ready to go back to work. Not nearly.


73
00:10:28.408 --> 00:10:30.994
Then what the hell was the point
in all of this?


74
00:10:47.553 --> 00:10:49.555
Don't forget what we talked about, okay?

75
00:10:51.848 --> 00:10:54.643
Organize yourself. 
Prep for memory gaps.

76
00:10:56.186 --> 00:10:59.356
Make lists. Keep your lists.
Put like with like.


77
00:10:59.439 --> 00:11:02.609
Find two of something,
put them together like we worked on.


78
00:11:02.693 --> 00:11:03.819
I'm not gonna forget.

79
00:11:04.945 --> 00:11:08.073
People do.
They can get a little ahead of themselves.


80
00:11:09.741 --> 00:11:13.287
Well, what's your plan for getting home
from the bus? We can write it down.


81
00:11:15.539 --> 00:11:18.208
My mom is gonna pick me up
from the bus station.


82
00:11:18.792 --> 00:11:20.252
Anyone else gonna be around?

83
00:11:21.461 --> 00:11:22.462
Your brother?

84
00:11:27.134 --> 00:11:30.345
I haven't really been home in a while,
and it's not like I'm staying for long.


85
00:11:30.429 --> 00:11:33.015
- So…
- It can help to be with people.


86
00:11:34.182 --> 00:11:35.183
I'm good on my own.

87
00:11:41.315 --> 00:11:45.652
Ativan, Depakote, Cymbalta, Vicodin.

88
00:11:46.361 --> 00:11:47.487
The rehab's not over.

89
00:11:49.072 --> 00:11:52.492
You're gonna have to work hard every day
to do all the things you used to do.


90
00:11:53.660 --> 00:11:54.661
Yep.

91
00:11:56.997 --> 00:11:57.998
I'm gonna be fine.

92
00:16:22.179 --> 00:16:24.598
You think you're so funny, don't you?

93
00:16:24.681 --> 00:16:26.516
I think it's in here. Hold on.

94
00:16:27.226 --> 00:16:29.853
Okay. I'll be right there. Hold on.

95
00:16:31.563 --> 00:16:32.564
Lynsey?

96
00:16:35.609 --> 00:16:38.528
Lynsey, I thought you said
you were coming on Friday.


97
00:16:39.571 --> 00:16:40.572
Mom?

98
00:16:45.035 --> 00:16:46.036
You okay?

99
00:16:48.121 --> 00:16:49.122
I'm fine.

100
00:16:53.919 --> 00:16:56.213
I asked Debbie to get off work
early Friday.


101
00:16:57.297 --> 00:17:00.425
I was gonna get groceries,
clean out the truck for you,


102
00:17:01.969 --> 00:17:05.513
get a cake, pick you up.
It was gonna be a homecoming on Friday.


103
00:17:06.598 --> 00:17:07.724
It's okay.

104
00:17:10.476 --> 00:17:11.770
Hey, you wanna meet Ted?

105
00:17:11.853 --> 00:17:14.397
No. I need to sleep.

106
00:17:15.523 --> 00:17:16.733
We'll keep it down.

107
00:17:17.609 --> 00:17:20.862
I gotta go to work early,
but you sleep in.


108
00:17:26.493 --> 00:17:27.494
Hey, Lyns.

109
00:17:29.913 --> 00:17:31.123
I was worried about you.

110
00:17:36.253 --> 00:17:37.254
You look like you.

111
00:18:42.778 --> 00:18:43.779
Can I help you?

112
00:18:45.155 --> 00:18:46.907
I was wondering if you're still hiring.

113
00:18:48.242 --> 00:18:49.993
- To clean pools?
- Yeah.


114
00:18:50.786 --> 00:18:53.330
You home for the summer? 
You in college?

115
00:18:55.040 --> 00:18:56.750
I just got back from Afghanistan.

116
00:18:57.918 --> 00:19:01.713
Thank you for your service.
My father was in the Navy. Korean.


117
00:19:02.798 --> 00:19:04.925
But why do you wanna clean pools?

118
00:19:06.552 --> 00:19:09.972
I like the water.
I used to clean the pools over at Newman.


119
00:19:10.472 --> 00:19:13.642
I guess there's not
a lot of swimming pools in Afghanistan.


120
00:19:14.226 --> 00:19:15.602
Not where I was. No.

121
00:19:16.562 --> 00:19:18.105
- Can you drive?
- Yeah.


122
00:19:19.147 --> 00:19:20.774
Great. Start tomorrow?

123
00:19:21.358 --> 00:19:22.484
Sure.

124
00:19:48.051 --> 00:19:50.387
Hey! Get the fuck off the road!

125
00:19:57.769 --> 00:20:00.063
Fuck! Fuck! Fuck!

126
00:20:02.357 --> 00:20:03.358
Fuck.

127
00:20:45.901 --> 00:20:47.152
Yeah.

128
00:20:49.029 --> 00:20:50.531
What's this, '85 Scottsdale?

129
00:20:51.490 --> 00:20:55.077
Old, old body style right here.
Got you a nice truck.


130
00:20:55.160 --> 00:20:57.079
Yeah. Not anymore.

131
00:20:58.080 --> 00:20:59.331
How long it been doing this?

132
00:20:59.414 --> 00:21:02.334
Just now. I don't know. 
It's not mine.

133
00:21:03.126 --> 00:21:04.920
When the last time
you changed the oil in it?


134
00:21:06.713 --> 00:21:07.756
I don't know.

135
00:21:09.883 --> 00:21:11.510
All right. It's all right.

136
00:21:12.261 --> 00:21:13.929
Hey, Santiago.

137
00:21:15.556 --> 00:21:16.557
You can wait inside.

138
00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:17.641
We got air in there.

139
00:21:19.685 --> 00:21:20.727
Yeah.

140
00:21:21.895 --> 00:21:24.898
Yesterday, I said
it was the exhaust valve, and I was right.


141
00:21:43.083 --> 00:21:46.003
So... Well, probably just the carburetor.

142
00:21:46.086 --> 00:21:48.088
And if it is,
I can just get that part on eBay.


143
00:21:48.171 --> 00:21:51.717
It ain't that hard to find. It may
take a while to get here. You in a hurry?


144
00:21:52.342 --> 00:21:54.011
I don't know how long I'll be here.

145
00:21:54.970 --> 00:21:59.516
- How much is it gonna cost?
- Maybe about 350, 400, plus labor.


146
00:22:00.225 --> 00:22:02.705
Maybe more if we get in there
and find it needs some more work.


147
00:22:02.769 --> 00:22:06.148
I don't know if I wanna fix it.
It's not even mine. It's...


148
00:22:06.231 --> 00:22:10.527
Oh, no, now that…
I mean, that's a nice truck.


149
00:22:12.487 --> 00:22:13.488
So…

150
00:22:16.533 --> 00:22:19.119
Okay, how about you just
leave it here with us?


151
00:22:19.203 --> 00:22:21.830
And when I get the part,
I'll call you for an estimate. Yeah?


152
00:22:23.332 --> 00:22:24.583
I don't know my number.

153
00:22:25.751 --> 00:22:26.960
I mean, it's just business.

154
00:22:27.711 --> 00:22:30.923
No. I really don't know my number.

155
00:22:36.178 --> 00:22:40.015
How about you... How about this?
How about you call me,


156
00:22:40.515 --> 00:22:42.267
and your number will show up. Okay?

157
00:22:43.393 --> 00:22:44.811
Can I see your phone?

158
00:22:45.312 --> 00:22:47.648
So what I'ma do
is I'ma call me, right?

159
00:22:48.774 --> 00:22:51.610
And that way, my number will show up,
all right? Simple as that.


160
00:22:52.527 --> 00:22:53.779
It's Aucoin.

161
00:22:54.404 --> 00:22:55.405
Thank you.

162
00:23:32.192 --> 00:23:35.320
Hey, '85 Scottsdale, you okay?

163
00:23:36.947 --> 00:23:37.948
I'm fine.

164
00:23:38.949 --> 00:23:41.076
I mean, it's real hot out.
You want a ride?


165
00:23:43.412 --> 00:23:44.413
Where you headed?

166
00:23:44.496 --> 00:23:46.248
Just down near Tchoup and Bordeaux.

167
00:23:48.125 --> 00:23:50.586
- Gonna get a sno-ball?
- No.


168
00:23:52.629 --> 00:23:53.797
Shit, maybe.

169
00:24:00.637 --> 00:24:02.389
Hey, you wanna play some music?

170
00:24:03.724 --> 00:24:05.142
You can pick whatever CD you like.

171
00:24:13.942 --> 00:24:15.694
My grandma used to play this record. She...

172
00:24:16.403 --> 00:24:18.322
Man, she loved her some Ernie.

173
00:24:19.907 --> 00:24:21.825
He's making a joke
out of the blues though.


174
00:24:22.409 --> 00:24:25.913
- You grew up here?
- Yeah, born and raised. You?


175
00:24:27.247 --> 00:24:28.248
Same.

176
00:24:28.832 --> 00:24:30.626
- Where you go to high school?
- Newman.


177
00:24:34.213 --> 00:24:35.672
I had a scholarship.

178
00:24:36.381 --> 00:24:37.925
I went to De La Salle.

179
00:24:39.885 --> 00:24:40.885
Aucoin, right?

180
00:24:41.803 --> 00:24:43.722
You know, most people,
they just call me James.


181
00:24:44.514 --> 00:24:46.892
I knew a Jess Aucoin
that went to De La Salle.


182
00:24:47.601 --> 00:24:49.061
That would be my sister.

183
00:24:49.144 --> 00:24:52.314
I played against her in basketball.
She was tough.


184
00:25:03.742 --> 00:25:05.011
The weirdest thing about this song

185
00:25:05.035 --> 00:25:07.454
is that he actually got buried
with his mother-in-law.


186
00:25:07.538 --> 00:25:08.830
Down on Claiborne.

187
00:25:09.498 --> 00:25:10.499
That's ironic.

188
00:25:14.086 --> 00:25:14.920
Shoot.

189
00:25:15.003 --> 00:25:17.214
I guess that's why
people don't buy CDs anymore.


190
00:25:17.297 --> 00:25:19.925
Know what? I'm old-school, so…

191
00:25:21.843 --> 00:25:22.844
Yeah.

192
00:25:28.684 --> 00:25:29.685
You know this one, right?

193
00:25:31.270 --> 00:25:34.398
- "Here Come the Girls"?
- That's it.


194
00:25:35.440 --> 00:25:36.441
Okay, Newman.

195
00:26:05.679 --> 00:26:06.680
All right.

196
00:26:07.848 --> 00:26:10.976
First you scrub,
then you use your skimmer.


197
00:26:11.059 --> 00:26:13.270
Get all your flowers and leaves
off the surface.


198
00:26:13.353 --> 00:26:15.397
Then you get your leaf rake.
That's the heavy net.


199
00:26:15.480 --> 00:26:18.025
You get all your rocks, twigs, acorns.

200
00:26:18.108 --> 00:26:20.611
Stuff that'll clog your main drain
and damage your pump.


201
00:26:20.694 --> 00:26:23.822
Hey, you okay? 
Can you handle all of that?

202
00:26:23.906 --> 00:26:25.782
Yeah. Main drain…

203
00:26:25.866 --> 00:26:29.453
All right, good.
So then you're gonna empty the drains.


204
00:26:30.245 --> 00:26:32.873
And the drains are serious.

205
00:26:33.790 --> 00:26:36.126
You don't know what's in those drains.

206
00:26:36.710 --> 00:26:40.380
You can tell a lot about a person
'cause of what's in their pool drains.


207
00:26:43.592 --> 00:26:46.094
You really gotta give it some more muscle.

208
00:26:49.431 --> 00:26:50.432
There you go.

209
00:26:51.308 --> 00:26:53.518
People treat their pools like shit.

210
00:26:54.603 --> 00:26:57.522
Out of chlorine.
Grabbing some from the truck.


211
00:27:06.031 --> 00:27:08.075
You think you can
handle this on your own?

212
00:27:08.659 --> 00:27:09.535
Yes, sir.

213
00:27:09.618 --> 00:27:11.870
Great. Then you can start
with Octavia Street tomorrow.


214
00:27:22.589 --> 00:27:26.426
Just come over after then. Yes, baby.

215
00:27:27.928 --> 00:27:29.388
Okay. I'll see you later.

216
00:27:32.349 --> 00:27:35.018
You're in here. 
I didn't see the truck.

217
00:27:36.103 --> 00:27:37.104
It's at the shop.

218
00:27:37.604 --> 00:27:40.065
What's wrong with it?
What's it gonna cost?


219
00:27:40.148 --> 00:27:42.442
Don't worry about it. 
I'll pay for it.

220
00:27:43.151 --> 00:27:44.361
That's not what I meant.

221
00:27:47.155 --> 00:27:48.156
How you feeling?

222
00:27:49.449 --> 00:27:51.827
Good. Okay. I'm good.

223
00:27:52.786 --> 00:27:56.164
Come sit with me awhile?
I could use a drink.


224
00:28:02.087 --> 00:28:03.255
You tired?

225
00:28:04.464 --> 00:28:05.465
Yeah.

226
00:28:07.467 --> 00:28:08.468
Right.

227
00:28:49.676 --> 00:28:51.803
Hello? Anybody home?

228
00:28:52.387 --> 00:28:53.805
I'm back here, James.

229
00:28:59.269 --> 00:29:00.729
Damn, this place is nice.

230
00:29:01.897 --> 00:29:04.524
- I ain't gonna get shot, am I?
- Not today.


231
00:29:05.025 --> 00:29:06.401
Owners are out of town.

232
00:29:09.154 --> 00:29:10.614
- Thanks.
- You're welcome.


233
00:29:13.742 --> 00:29:16.119
- Do you wanna sit down?
- Yeah.


234
00:29:26.004 --> 00:29:27.005
Do you swim?

235
00:29:32.928 --> 00:29:34.346
Not exactly, no.

236
00:29:34.972 --> 00:29:38.475
- I saw it in your walk.
- I get around okay.


237
00:29:40.018 --> 00:29:41.019
Did you serve?

238
00:29:42.354 --> 00:29:45.440
No. I take it you did?

239
00:29:46.608 --> 00:29:48.944
Something like that. 
I just got back.

240
00:29:50.279 --> 00:29:51.280
How's it going?

241
00:29:55.158 --> 00:29:56.702
- Yeah.
- Yeah.


242
00:29:59.621 --> 00:30:01.123
And look straight up.

243
00:30:07.254 --> 00:30:08.463
And now the left.

244
00:30:12.301 --> 00:30:13.302
Very good.

245
00:30:15.262 --> 00:30:22.019
So, Ativan, Cymbalta, Depakote, Vicodin
and a brain injury.


246
00:30:24.021 --> 00:30:26.440
From which you appear to be recovering
extremely well.


247
00:30:28.150 --> 00:30:30.903
With brain injuries,
there are never any guarantees.


248
00:30:31.528 --> 00:30:34.448
I'm feeling pretty good.
In fact, I'd like to know


249
00:30:34.531 --> 00:30:38.660
what would happen
if I stopped taking the medication?


250
00:30:38.744 --> 00:30:43.290
You'd be a high risk of seizure, anxiety,
withdrawal and depression.


251
00:30:43.373 --> 00:30:44.374
I feel fine.

252
00:30:45.417 --> 00:30:48.629
Is it possible you feel fine
because of the Cymbalta?


253
00:30:51.381 --> 00:30:54.343
Could you explain to me
what caused the brain injury?


254
00:30:55.886 --> 00:30:57.012
Doesn't it say in there?

255
00:30:57.596 --> 00:31:00.265
